english:
  title: Two Poems in the Ancient Style
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I. The Majestic Phoenix

    A phoenix dwells deep in the forest,
    worse off than any bird in a gilded cage.
    Wings and feathers shattered to bits,
    a solitary frame stands bare and stark.

    I recall those days of soaring flight,
    when ancient parasol trees stood a thousand years strong.
    Eagles and hawks came from the northwest,
    rearing their young through the long days and nights.
    When the partridge sang in the southern hills,
    it had fortune enough to find a companion,
    but the partridge was careless and loose-tongued—
    so the hawk brought it down.

    All the crows pass by with folded wings.
    Who among them thinks of the phoenix's fate?
    O phoenix, I beg you—do not move,
    for one peck leaves nothing of your flesh.

    II. The Orchid Tree on the Cliff

    The orchid tree stands verdant and tall,
    its beauty rising a thousand fathoms up the cliff face.
    Its lonely roots lay bare on the stone's jagged teeth,
    enduring harsh winds and bitter rains.

    The climbing vines, with joints unnumbered,
    extend their tendrils in tender support.
    The ivy creeps through and around,
    its fragrant blooms drift sweet through day and night.
    Interdependent, they hold back the threatening storm,
    propping up what would fall—this is their deepest wish.

    But one evening, like sparks of starfire,
    turbulence arose and shattered all hope.
    Frost came cruel and covered the tender branches,
    the joints gave way until only withered roots remained.

    The orchid tree can only wish to stand firm,
    and if it must surrender its life—what sorrow is there in that?
  footnotes:
    - This poem is attributed to Liang Jianwen (梁簡文), a 6th-century Southern Liang emperor known for his literary patronage and refined taste.
    - The second poem references Tang Wenzong (唐文宗), a 9th-century Tang emperor whose reign witnessed considerable political turmoil and court instability.
    - The 'partridge' (자고/鷓鴣) and 'orchid tree' (목란/木蘭) are common symbols in East Asian poetry for nobility, refinement, and moral virtue under duress.
    - Kim Jong-jik composed these poems using the 'ancient style' (고풍/古風) form, which allowed poets to address contemporary political concerns through historical and allegorical references.
